-- ============================================================
-- Quiz Seed: 2 Kings Chapters 21–25
-- Target table: chapter_quizzes
-- Difficulties: kids (3 Qs), teens (5 Qs), adults (8 Qs)
-- correct_answer is always 'a'
-- ============================================================

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
-- CHAPTERS 21 – 25
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════

-- ═══ 2 Kings Chapter 21 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Kings', 21, 'kids', 1, 'Who was the wickedest king of Judah, who reigned for fifty-five years?', 'Manasseh', 'Amon', 'Ahaz', 'Jehoram', 'a', 'Manasseh was twelve years old when he began to reign, and reigned five and fifty years in Jerusalem (2 Kings 21:1).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'kids', 2, 'What terrible thing did Manasseh do to his own son?', 'He made his son pass through the fire', 'He sold his son to a foreign king', 'He banished his son from the palace', 'He offered his son to a false prophet', 'a', 'He made his son pass through the fire, and observed times, and used enchantments, and dealt with familiar spirits and wizards (2 Kings 21:6).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'kids', 3, 'How long did Amon, Manasseh''s son, reign before he was killed?', 'Two years', 'Ten years', 'Twenty years', 'Five years', 'a', 'Amon was twenty and two years old when he began to reign, and he reigned two years in Jerusalem (2 Kings 21:19).'),
-- Teens
('2 Kings', 21, 'teens', 1, 'What abomination did Manasseh set up inside the temple itself?', 'A carved image of Asherah', 'The golden calf of Jeroboam', 'An altar to Baal covered with bronze', 'A carved image of Nisroch the Assyrian god', 'a', 'He set a graven image of the grove that he had made in the house, of which the LORD said to David, and to Solomon his son, In this house, and in Jerusalem...will I put my name for ever (2 Kings 21:7).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'teens', 2, 'What verdict did God pronounce on Jerusalem because of Manasseh''s sins?', 'I will wipe Jerusalem as a man wipeth a dish, wiping it, and turning it upside down', 'Jerusalem shall burn like Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Jerusalem shall be scattered to the four winds', 'Jerusalem shall become a desolation like the wilderness', 'a', 'I will wipe Jerusalem as a man wipeth a dish, wiping it, and turning it upside down (2 Kings 21:13).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'teens', 3, 'With what did God say He would measure and plumb Jerusalem for judgment?', 'The line of Samaria, and the plummet of the house of Ahab', 'The measuring rod of Moses and the plumb line of the prophets', 'The standard of the nations and the cord of Egypt', 'The rod of the Assyrian king and the cord of Babylon', 'a', 'I will stretch over Jerusalem the line of Samaria, and the plummet of the house of Ahab (2 Kings 21:13).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'teens', 4, 'Who killed King Amon, and who then became king?', 'His own servants; then Josiah his son', 'A conspiracy of princes; then Jehoahaz', 'An unnamed prophet; then Hezekiah''s grandson', 'The people of the land; then his brother', 'a', 'His servants conspired against him, and slew the king in his own house. And the people of the land slew all them that had conspired against king Amon; and the people of the land made Josiah his son king in his stead (2 Kings 21:23-24).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'teens', 5, 'According to the prophets, what specific sin filled Jerusalem from one end to another?', 'Innocent blood', 'Idolatry and sorcery', 'Theft and false witness', 'Adultery and violence', 'a', 'Manasseh shed innocent blood very much, till he had filled Jerusalem from one end to another (2 Kings 21:16).'),
-- Adults
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 1, 'What specific comparison is made between Manasseh''s sins and the nations God expelled from Canaan?', 'He did after the abominations of the heathen, whom the LORD cast out before the children of Israel', 'His sins exceeded those of the Canaanites in every respect', 'He restored only the practices that the Canaanites had abandoned', 'His sins were similar to but not as severe as those of the Amorites', 'a', 'He did that which was evil in the sight of the LORD, after the abominations of the heathen, whom the LORD cast out before the children of Israel (2 Kings 21:2).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 2, 'What altars did Manasseh build in the two courts of the house of the LORD?', 'He built altars for all the host of heaven in the two courts of the house of the LORD', 'He built altars to Baal and Asherah in the inner and outer courts', 'He built a single great altar to Molech in the outer court', 'He built altars to the gods of Assyria in the treasury courts', 'a', 'He built altars for all the host of heaven in the two courts of the house of the LORD (2 Kings 21:5).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 3, 'How does the text describe Manasseh''s seduction of Judah into sin?', 'Manasseh seduced them to do more evil than did the nations whom the LORD destroyed before the children of Israel', 'He forced them through legal decrees to worship the Asherah', 'He deceived the priests into accepting foreign worship as Mosaic', 'He bribed the prophets to endorse his religious innovations', 'a', 'Manasseh seduced them to do more evil than did the nations whom the LORD destroyed before the children of Israel (2 Kings 21:9).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 4, 'What does the oracle in verses 12-15 say will happen to everyone who hears of Jerusalem''s coming judgment?', 'Both his ears shall tingle', 'The nations shall tremble at the sound of her fall', 'All who hear shall clap their hands and rejoice', 'The prophets of the nations shall foretell it', 'a', 'Whosoever heareth of it, both his ears shall tingle (2 Kings 21:12).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 5, 'What does the phrase "the LORD''s anger was kindled against Judah" following Manasseh''s reign signal about the subsequent narrative of Kings?', 'It establishes that even Josiah''s later reforms could not reverse the divine decision to exile Judah, as confirmed in 2 Kings 23:26', 'It means God immediately sent Babylon to destroy Jerusalem in Manasseh''s lifetime', 'It is merely a formulaic expression with no bearing on later events', 'It was reversed when Manasseh repented late in his reign', 'a', 'Notwithstanding the LORD turned not from the fierceness of his great wrath (2 Kings 23:26), and 2 Kings 21:15 states that Manasseh''s sins provoked God''s anger — confirmed by Jeremiah 15:4 which names Manasseh as the cause of Judah''s eventual exile.'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 6, 'What occult practices are explicitly listed as part of Manasseh''s sin?', 'He observed times, used enchantments, dealt with familiar spirits and wizards', 'He offered burnt sacrifices to stars and cast lots before the Asherah', 'He employed Philistine diviners and consulted the Urim illegally', 'He sacrificed white bulls at each new moon to Baal', 'a', 'He observed times, and used enchantments, and dealt with familiar spirits and wizards: he wrought much wickedness in the sight of the LORD (2 Kings 21:6).'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 7, 'What is the theological significance of the fact that the people of the land executed Amon''s assassins and made Josiah king?', 'It shows a popular loyalty to the Davidic line that resisted palace coups, preserving the covenant dynasty', 'It shows the army controlled the succession to the throne', 'It indicates the people were entirely wicked and chose Josiah for political reasons', 'It fulfilled a specific prophecy made to Solomon at the temple dedication', 'a', 'The people of the land slew all them that had conspired against king Amon; and the people of the land made Josiah his son king in his stead (2 Kings 21:24), showing a popular instinct to maintain the Davidic line even in a morally degraded age.'),
('2 Kings', 21, 'adults', 8, 'How does 2 Chronicles 33 supplement the account in 2 Kings 21 regarding Manasseh''s ultimate fate?', '2 Chronicles records that Manasseh was taken captive to Babylon, humbled himself, prayed to God, was restored to Jerusalem, and removed foreign altars — a repentance not mentioned in Kings', '2 Chronicles confirms every detail of 2 Kings 21 without addition', '2 Chronicles records that Manasseh died in Assyrian captivity and was never restored', '2 Chronicles says Manasseh built the temple portico as an act of contrition', 'a', '2 Chronicles 33:11-13 records that the Assyrians took Manasseh captive, and when he was in affliction, he besought the LORD...and God was intreated of him — a repentance the Kings account omits, perhaps because Kings judges him by the lasting effect of his sins on Judah.');

-- ═══ 2 Kings Chapter 22 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Kings', 22, 'kids', 1, 'What important book was found in the temple during Josiah''s repairs?', 'The book of the law', 'The book of the kings of Judah', 'The scroll of Isaiah', 'The book of Deuteronomy of Ezra', 'a', 'Hilkiah the high priest said unto Shaphan the scribe, I have found the book of the law in the house of the LORD (2 Kings 22:8).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'kids', 2, 'How old was Josiah when he became king?', 'Eight years old', 'Twelve years old', 'Sixteen years old', 'Seven years old', 'a', 'Josiah was eight years old when he began to reign, and he reigned thirty and one years in Jerusalem (2 Kings 22:1).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'kids', 3, 'Who was the prophetess that Josiah''s servants went to consult about the book of the law?', 'Huldah the prophetess', 'Deborah the judge', 'Miriam the sister of Moses', 'Anna the prophetess', 'a', 'Hilkiah the priest...went unto Huldah the prophetess (2 Kings 22:14).'),
-- Teens
('2 Kings', 22, 'teens', 1, 'What was Josiah''s overall spiritual assessment compared to other kings?', 'He did that which was right in the sight of the LORD, and walked in all the way of David his father, and turned not aside to the right hand or to the left', 'He was righteous but did not remove the high places', 'He was as good as Hezekiah but less faithful than David', 'He followed the LORD only until the book was found', 'a', 'He did that which was right in the sight of the LORD, and walked in all the way of David his father, and turned not aside to the right hand or to the left (2 Kings 22:2).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'teens', 2, 'How did Josiah react when the book of the law was read to him?', 'He rent his clothes', 'He called an immediate fast', 'He wept before the LORD for seven days', 'He summoned all the priests to read it again', 'a', 'When the king had heard the words of the book of the law, that he rent his clothes (2 Kings 22:11).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'teens', 3, 'Who was Hilkiah the high priest and what else is he notable for in this chapter?', 'He found the book of the law and sent it to Shaphan the scribe, who read it before the king', 'He repaired the temple treasury and reorganised the Levitical service', 'He was the father of Jeremiah the prophet', 'He wrote the book of the law and then hid it for safekeeping', 'a', 'Hilkiah the high priest said unto Shaphan the scribe, I have found the book of the law in the house of the LORD. And Hilkiah gave the book to Shaphan, and he read it (2 Kings 22:8).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'teens', 4, 'Where did Huldah the prophetess live in Jerusalem?', 'In the college', 'In the palace district', 'In the temple precincts', 'In the lower city', 'a', 'She dwelt in Jerusalem in the college (2 Kings 22:14).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'teens', 5, 'What did Huldah prophesy would happen to Josiah personally because he humbled himself?', 'He would be gathered to his grave in peace, and his eyes would not see all the evil coming on Jerusalem', 'He would live to see Babylon''s defeat and Jerusalem''s restoration', 'He would be given thirty more years of life like Hezekiah', 'He would be honoured above all kings of Judah before him', 'a', 'Because thine heart was tender, and thou hast humbled thyself before the LORD...thou shalt be gathered into thy grave in peace; and thine eyes shall not see all the evil which I will bring upon this place (2 Kings 22:19-20).'),
-- Adults
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 1, 'What specific work was being done on the temple when the book of the law was found?', 'The house was being repaired with money collected at the door by the Levites, disbursed to carpenters, builders, and masons', 'A new outer court was being constructed on the north side', 'The bronze pillars were being replaced with new ones', 'The inner sanctuary was being re-gilded with donated gold', 'a', 'Shaphan...told the king, saying, Thy servants have gathered the money that was found in the house, and have delivered it into the hand of them that do the work, that have the oversight of the house of the LORD (2 Kings 22:9).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 2, 'To whom did King Josiah instruct Hilkiah to go and enquire of the LORD?', 'Go ye, enquire of the LORD for me, and for the people, and for all Judah, concerning the words of this book that is found', 'Go to the elders of Judah and ask them to interpret the law', 'Go to the temple in Bethel where the Levites keep records', 'Go to the Urim and Thummim for a divine answer', 'a', 'The king commanded Hilkiah the priest...saying, Go ye, enquire of the LORD for me, and for the people, and for all Judah, concerning the words of this book that is found (2 Kings 22:12-13).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 3, 'What specific message did Huldah declare about the fate of Jerusalem and Judah?', 'Behold, I will bring evil upon this place, and upon the inhabitants thereof, even all the words of the book which the king of Judah hath read', 'Jerusalem shall be spared for forty years if the people repent', 'The evil shall come but not in the generation of the king''s sons', 'A remnant shall be preserved in the city even when Babylon comes', 'a', 'Thus saith the LORD, Behold, I will bring evil upon this place, and upon the inhabitants thereof, even all the words of the book which the king of Judah hath read (2 Kings 22:16).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 4, 'What was the sin that Huldah identified as the reason God''s wrath was not quenched?', 'They have forsaken me, and have burned incense unto other gods, that they might provoke me to anger with all the works of their hands', 'They had shed innocent blood in the temple courts', 'They had stopped keeping the Passover for three generations', 'They had disobeyed the law on tithes and firstfruits', 'a', 'Because they have forsaken me, and have burned incense unto other gods, that they might provoke me to anger with all the works of their hands; therefore my wrath shall be kindled against this place, and shall not be quenched (2 Kings 22:17).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 5, 'What is the scholarly consensus about the identity of the "book of the law" found in the temple?', 'Most scholars identify it as Deuteronomy or a substantial portion thereof, based on the reforms Josiah subsequently undertook which parallel Deuteronomic law', 'It was the complete Pentateuch transcribed by Ezra from memory', 'It was the book of the covenant from Exodus 20-23 only', 'It was a prophetic collection mistakenly called the law', 'a', 'The book found in the temple (2 Kings 22:8) is widely identified with Deuteronomy because Josiah''s subsequent reforms — centralising worship, abolishing high places, celebrating Passover — all correspond to the specific requirements of Deuteronomy.'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 6, 'What does the tenderness of Josiah''s heart, cited by Huldah, contrast with in the broader narrative of Kings?', 'It contrasts sharply with Manasseh''s hardened heart that filled Jerusalem with innocent blood and Amon''s brief, unreformed reign', 'It contrasts with Hezekiah''s weeping, showing Josiah responded more actively', 'It contrasts with Solomon''s wisdom, showing that humility surpasses knowledge', 'It contrasts with the prophets who warned Israel without personal grief', 'a', 'Huldah said, because thine heart was tender (2 Kings 22:19), in sharp contrast to Manasseh who shed innocent blood very much (2 Kings 21:16) and Amon who did evil and humbled not himself (2 Chronicles 33:23).'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 7, 'What does Huldah''s role as prophetess suggest about the status of women in prophetic ministry in Israel?', 'Women could hold genuine prophetic authority; Josiah''s court treated her word as authoritative on par with male prophets including Jeremiah and Zephaniah who were contemporary', 'She was consulted only because the male prophets were unavailable', 'She was a lesser prophetess whose word required male confirmation', 'Her role was exceptional and had no precedent or successor in Israel', 'a', 'Josiah''s delegation went to Huldah the prophetess (2 Kings 22:14), treating her oracle as authoritative — notably at a time when both Jeremiah and Zephaniah were active prophets, suggesting she was the court''s preferred prophetic voice.'),
('2 Kings', 22, 'adults', 8, 'How does the promise that Josiah would be gathered to his grave in peace relate to his actual death at Megiddo in 2 Kings 23:29?', 'The peace refers to his not living to witness the Babylonian sack of Jerusalem rather than dying peacefully in battle — he was spared the greater calamity, not guaranteed a natural death', 'The prophecy was simply wrong because Josiah disobeyed God at Megiddo', 'Josiah died peacefully of wounds sustained at Megiddo in his own palace', 'The peace referred to his eternal rest with his ancestors in the covenantal promise', 'a', 'Thou shalt be gathered into thy grave in peace (2 Kings 22:20) means Josiah would not see the Babylonian destruction of Jerusalem — his death at Megiddo (2 Kings 23:29) preceded the exile, so he was spared witnessing Jerusalem''s fall, which is the specific evil Huldah described.');

-- ═══ 2 Kings Chapter 23 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Kings', 23, 'kids', 1, 'What great feast did Josiah restore that had not been kept properly for a very long time?', 'The Passover', 'The Feast of Tabernacles', 'The Day of Atonement', 'The Feast of Firstfruits', 'a', 'The king commanded all the people, saying, Keep the passover unto the LORD your God (2 Kings 23:21).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'kids', 2, 'Where was King Josiah killed in battle?', 'Megiddo', 'Jerusalem', 'Jericho', 'Samaria', 'a', 'Pharaoh-nechoh...slew him at Megiddo, when he had seen him (2 Kings 23:29).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'kids', 3, 'What did Josiah do to the altars and high places throughout the land?', 'He defiled and broke them down', 'He offered sacrifices on them to the LORD', 'He rebuilt them as storehouses', 'He left them standing but unused', 'a', 'He defiled Topheth...and he brake down the altars that were on the top of the upper chamber of Ahaz...and brake down the high places (2 Kings 23:10, 12).'),
-- Teens
('2 Kings', 23, 'teens', 1, 'What was the covenant Josiah made standing by a pillar in the temple?', 'To walk after the LORD, and to keep his commandments and his testimonies and his statutes with all their heart and all their soul', 'To rebuild the temple entirely with pure cedar from Lebanon', 'To execute all priests who had served at the high places', 'To make annual war against all idolatrous nations surrounding Judah', 'a', 'The king stood by a pillar, and made a covenant before the LORD, to walk after the LORD, and to keep his commandments and his testimonies and his statutes with all their heart and all their soul (2 Kings 23:3).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'teens', 2, 'What ancient prophecy from 1 Kings 13 did Josiah fulfil at Bethel?', 'He burned men''s bones upon the altar at Bethel, defiling the high place of Jeroboam, just as a man of God had cried against the altar by the word of the LORD', 'He tore down the golden calf of Bethel as a prophet had foretold', 'He built a new altar at Bethel to replace Jeroboam''s, as prophesied', 'He killed the priests of Bethel as an unnamed prophet had foretold three hundred years earlier', 'a', 'He burnt men''s bones upon it, and defiled it, according to the word of the LORD which the man of God proclaimed, who proclaimed these words (2 Kings 23:16).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'teens', 3, 'What statement is made about Josiah compared to all other kings of Judah?', 'Like unto him was there no king before him, that turned to the LORD with all his heart, and with all his soul, and with all his might', 'He was greater than David in obedience and greater than Solomon in wisdom', 'He was the most militarily successful king Judah had ever produced', 'He was the only king to fulfil every word of the prophets', 'a', 'Like unto him was there no king before him, that turned to the LORD with all his heart, and with all his soul, and with all his might, according to all the law of Moses; neither after him arose there any like him (2 Kings 23:25).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'teens', 4, 'What was the result of Josiah''s unparalleled righteousness on God''s plan to judge Judah?', 'The LORD turned not from the fierceness of his great wrath because of all the provocations of Manasseh', 'God cancelled the judgment entirely as He had done for Hezekiah', 'God delayed the exile for one hundred years', 'God sent only a partial judgment destroying the north but sparing Jerusalem', 'a', 'Notwithstanding the LORD turned not from the fierceness of his great wrath, wherewith his anger was kindled against Judah, because of all the provocations that Manasseh had provoked him withal (2 Kings 23:26).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'teens', 5, 'Who succeeded Josiah and what happened to him?', 'Jehoahaz his son reigned three months then Pharaoh-nechoh put him in bands at Riblah and made Eliakim king in his place', 'Jehoiachin his son reigned three months then was taken to Babylon', 'Zedekiah his son reigned eleven years then fled from Jerusalem', 'Jehoram his son reigned two years then was removed by the people of the land', 'a', 'Pharaoh-nechoh put him in bands at Riblah in the land of Hamath, that he might not reign in Jerusalem (2 Kings 23:33).'),
-- Adults
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 1, 'What happened to the book of the covenant in the context of the renewal ceremony described in verse 2?', 'The king read in their ears all the words of the book of the covenant which was found in the house of the LORD', 'It was placed in the ark of the covenant for safekeeping', 'It was copied by the priests and distributed to every city', 'It was translated into the language of the northern exiles', 'a', 'The king went up into the house of the LORD...and he read in their ears all the words of the book of the covenant which was found in the house of the LORD (2 Kings 23:2).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 2, 'What was the cultic site of Topheth and what did Josiah do to it?', 'It was a site in the valley of Hinnom where children were burned in sacrifice to Molech; Josiah defiled it so it could no longer be used', 'It was the sacred grove of Asherah in the Kidron Valley; Josiah cut it down', 'It was a high place north of Jerusalem; Josiah demolished it and burned the stones', 'It was the pagan altar built by Manasseh in the temple courts; Josiah smashed it', 'a', 'He defiled Topheth, which is in the valley of the children of Hinnom, that no man might make his son or his daughter to pass through the fire to Molech (2 Kings 23:10).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 3, 'What did Josiah do with the horses that the kings of Judah had given to the sun?', 'He took away the horses that the kings of Judah had given to the sun at the entering in of the house of the LORD, and burned the chariots of the sun with fire', 'He slaughtered them as a sacrifice at the temple', 'He gave them to the Levites for the temple service', 'He sent them to Egypt as tribute', 'a', 'He took away the horses that the kings of Judah had given to the sun, at the entering in of the house of the LORD...and burned the chariots of the sun with fire (2 Kings 23:11).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 4, 'What was extraordinary about the Passover Josiah kept, compared to the entire history of the judges and kings?', 'Surely there was not holden such a passover from the days of the judges that judged Israel, nor in all the days of the kings of Israel, nor of the kings of Judah', 'It was celebrated with a larger number of animals than any previous Passover', 'It was the first Passover ever celebrated outside Jerusalem', 'It lasted fourteen days instead of the customary seven', 'a', 'Surely there was not holden such a passover from the days of the judges that judged Israel, nor in all the days of the kings of Israel, nor of the kings of Judah (2 Kings 23:22).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 5, 'What did Josiah do to the priests of the high places, distinguishing between those in Judah and those in Samaria?', 'He slew all the priests of the high places...in Samaria; but in Judah he brought the priests of the high places to Jerusalem but did not allow them to minister at the altar', 'He executed all priests of high places in both Judah and Samaria equally', 'He restored the priests of Judah''s high places to temple service after they repented', 'He sent the priests of Samaria to Assyria and retired the priests of Judah to their towns', 'a', 'He slew all the priests of the high places...in Samaria (2 Kings 23:20); but in Judah he brought all the priests of the high places to Jerusalem...but they did not come up to the altar of the LORD in Jerusalem (2 Kings 23:8-9).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 6, 'What was the name Pharaoh-nechoh gave to the new king he installed after deposing Jehoahaz, and what does the name change signify?', 'He made Eliakim the son of Josiah king in the room of Josiah his father, and turned his name to Jehoiakim — a name change signifying Egyptian suzerainty over Judah', 'He installed Zedekiah and changed his name to mark Babylonian submission', 'He renamed Jehoahaz as Shallum to mark his captivity', 'He named a new king from outside the Davidic line as a vassal ruler', 'a', 'Pharaoh-nechoh made Eliakim the son of Josiah king in the room of Josiah his father, and turned his name to Jehoiakim (2 Kings 23:34). Name changes in the ancient Near East signalled sovereign authority over the renamed person.'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 7, 'What taxation did Pharaoh-nechoh impose on Judah and how did Jehoiakim collect it?', 'He taxed the land a hundred talents of silver and a talent of gold; Jehoiakim exacted the silver and the gold of the people of the land, of every one according to his taxation', 'He demanded annual tribute of fifty talents of silver paid from the temple treasury', 'He required Judah to provide one thousand soldiers for Egyptian campaigns', 'He imposed a per-capita head tax of one shekel on every male over twenty', 'a', 'He taxed the land a hundred talents of silver, and a talent of gold. And Jehoiakim gave the silver and the gold to Pharaoh; but he taxed the land to give the money according to the commandment of Pharaoh: he exacted the silver and the gold of the people of the land, of every one according to his taxation (2 Kings 23:33, 35).'),
('2 Kings', 23, 'adults', 8, 'What theological tension does Josiah''s death at Megiddo create in the context of Huldah''s prophecy and the Deuteronomic principle that obedience brings blessing?', 'It challenges simplistic retribution theology — the most righteous king died young in battle, forcing readers to trust in God''s larger redemptive purposes and eschatological justice rather than immediate earthly reward', 'It proves that Deuteronomic theology was wrong and righteousness does not affect outcomes', 'It shows that Josiah must have sinned secretly and his death was punishment', 'It confirms that the covenant blessings applied only to the nation as a whole, never to individual kings', 'a', 'Josiah — the most faithful king in Israel''s history (2 Kings 23:25) — died at Megiddo at the hand of Pharaoh-nechoh (2 Kings 23:29), a fact that challenged Israel''s understanding of divine justice and pointed forward to the suffering servant who would also die obedient and apparently abandoned (cf. Isaiah 53).');

-- ═══ 2 Kings Chapter 24 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Kings', 24, 'kids', 1, 'Which great king came against Jerusalem and made Jehoiakim his servant for three years?', 'Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon', 'Pharaoh-nechoh king of Egypt', 'Tiglath-pileser king of Assyria', 'Sennacherib king of Assyria', 'a', 'Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came up, and Jehoiakim became his servant three years (2 Kings 24:1).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'kids', 2, 'Who was taken captive to Babylon with all his household, servants, princes, and officers?', 'Jehoiachin', 'Jehoiakim', 'Zedekiah', 'Josiah', 'a', 'Jehoiachin the king of Judah went out to the king of Babylon, he, and his mother, and his servants, and his princes, and his officers (2 Kings 24:12).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'kids', 3, 'Who did Nebuchadnezzar make king of Judah after taking Jehoiachin captive?', 'Mattaniah, whose name he changed to Zedekiah', 'Jehoahaz the son of Josiah', 'Shallum the son of Jabesh', 'An Assyrian governor', 'a', 'The king of Babylon made Mattaniah his father''s brother king in his stead, and changed his name to Zedekiah (2 Kings 24:17).'),
-- Teens
('2 Kings', 24, 'teens', 1, 'What enemies did God send against Jehoiakim because of the sins of Manasseh?', 'Bands of the Chaldees, bands of the Syrians, bands of the Moabites, and bands of the children of Ammon', 'The full army of Babylon alone', 'The Philistines from the west and the Edomites from the south', 'Pestilence, famine, and wild animals as covenant curses', 'a', 'The LORD sent against him bands of the Chaldees, and bands of the Syrians, and bands of the Moabites, and bands of the children of Ammon (2 Kings 24:2).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'teens', 2, 'How long did Jehoiachin reign before he surrendered to Nebuchadnezzar?', 'Three months', 'One year', 'Six months', 'Three years', 'a', 'Jehoiachin was eighteen years old when he began to reign, and he reigned in Jerusalem three months (2 Kings 24:8).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'teens', 3, 'What treasures did Nebuchadnezzar carry out of the temple and palace?', 'He carried out thence all the treasures of the house of the LORD, and the treasures of the king''s house, and cut in pieces all the vessels of gold which Solomon had made', 'Only the silver and gold, leaving the sacred vessels untouched', 'The ark of the covenant and the bronze altar', 'All the grain stores and livestock of Jerusalem', 'a', 'He carried out thence all the treasures of the house of the LORD, and the treasures of the king''s house, and cut in pieces all the vessels of gold which Solomon king of Israel had made in the temple of the LORD (2 Kings 24:13).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'teens', 4, 'How many people were carried away in the deportation of Jehoiachin?', 'Ten thousand captives, including all the princes, mighty men, craftsmen, and smiths; only the poorest people remained', 'Twenty thousand captives from across all Judah', 'Five thousand captives, only from Jerusalem', 'One thousand of the nobility and priests', 'a', 'He carried away all Jerusalem, and all the princes, and all the mighty men of valour, even ten thousand captives, and all the craftsmen and smiths (2 Kings 24:14).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'teens', 5, 'What was Zedekiah''s relationship to Jehoiachin, and how long did he reign?', 'Zedekiah was Jehoiachin''s uncle; he reigned eleven years', 'Zedekiah was Jehoiachin''s brother; he reigned seven years', 'Zedekiah was Jehoiachin''s son; he reigned three months', 'Zedekiah was Jehoiachin''s cousin; he reigned fifteen years', 'a', 'Zedekiah was twenty and one years old when he began to reign, and he reigned eleven years in Jerusalem...he was the uncle of Jehoiachin, i.e. the king of Babylon made his father''s brother king (2 Kings 24:17-18).'),
-- Adults
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 1, 'What theological explanation is given for the disasters coming upon Judah in Jehoiakim''s reign?', 'Surely at the commandment of the LORD came this upon Judah, to remove them out of his sight, for the sins of Manasseh', 'It was simply the consequence of political miscalculation in rebelling against Babylon', 'God was testing Judah''s faith as He had tested Abraham', 'The judgment came because Jehoiakim had broken the specific covenant Josiah had made', 'a', 'Surely at the commandment of the LORD came this upon Judah, to remove them out of his sight, for the sins of Manasseh, according to all that he did (2 Kings 24:3).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 2, 'What specific wording underlines that the disaster on Judah was not merely human political agency?', 'The LORD would not pardon', 'Nebuchadnezzar acted independently of any divine purpose', 'The prophets had warned but God had changed His mind', 'The people repented but it was too late for this generation', 'a', 'For through the anger of the LORD it came to pass in Jerusalem and Judah, until he had cast them out from his presence (2 Kings 24:20), making clear that Babylon was God''s instrument, not merely a geopolitical power.'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 3, 'What does the removal of all the craftsmen and smiths from Jerusalem signify strategically and symbolically?', 'Strategically it crippled Judah''s ability to manufacture weapons; symbolically it stripped the city of the skilled labour needed to maintain its structures and self-sufficiency', 'It was purely punitive with no military motive', 'It fulfilled a specific prophecy of Amos about Jerusalem''s artisans', 'It was done to rebuild Babylon''s temples using Judahite skilled workers', 'a', 'All the craftsmen and smiths...none remained, save the poorest sort of the people of the land (2 Kings 24:14), leaving Jerusalem economically and militarily defenceless, unable to forge weapons or maintain walls — a deliberate Babylonian strategy of subjugation.'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 4, 'How does the deportation of Jehoiachin relate to Jeremiah''s prophetic ministry?', 'Jeremiah 22:24-30 explicitly addressed Jehoiachin (Coniah), declaring him a "despised broken idol" and pronouncing that no descendant would sit on David''s throne — making the continuation of the Messianic line through his line theologically complex', 'Jeremiah approved of Jehoiachin and urged surrender as God''s will', 'Jeremiah''s prophecy about Jehoiachin was the one prediction that did not come true', 'Jeremiah never mentioned Jehoiachin by name', 'a', 'Jeremiah 22:28-30 asked, Is this man Coniah a despised broken idol?...thus saith the LORD, Write ye this man childless...for no man of his seed shall prosper, sitting upon the throne of David — a prophecy Matthew 1 resolves by tracing Jesus''s legal Davidic line through Jehoiachin but biological line through Nathan (Luke 3).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 5, 'What name change does the text record for Zedekiah and what does it imply about his status?', 'His name was Mattaniah before Nebuchadnezzar renamed him Zedekiah, marking him as a Babylonian vassal king ruling at Babylon''s pleasure', 'His name was Shallum and the people renamed him Zedekiah at his coronation', 'He renamed himself Zedekiah as a religious act of dedicating his reign to the LORD', 'Nebuchadnezzar renamed him from Eliakim to Zedekiah', 'a', 'The king of Babylon made Mattaniah...king in his stead, and changed his name to Zedekiah (2 Kings 24:17), a public name-change signalling Babylonian suzerainty, paralleling the Egyptian renaming of Eliakim to Jehoiakim (2 Kings 23:34).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 6, 'What spiritual assessment is given of Zedekiah?', 'He did that which was evil in the sight of the LORD, according to all that Jehoiakim had done', 'He was righteous in his early years but fell into idolatry when Jerusalem was besieged', 'He was the most wicked king since Manasseh', 'He did what was right in the sight of the LORD like his ancestor Hezekiah', 'a', 'He did that which was evil in the sight of the LORD, according to all that Jehoiakim had done (2 Kings 24:19).'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 7, 'What event triggers the final chapter''s narrative of Jerusalem''s destruction?', 'Zedekiah rebelled against the king of Babylon', 'A Babylonian invasion launched without provocation', 'Zedekiah sought help from Egypt and Babylon discovered the plot', 'An earthquake destroyed Jerusalem''s walls making them indefensible', 'a', 'Zedekiah rebelled against the king of Babylon (2 Kings 24:20), setting in motion the siege and destruction narrated in chapter 25.'),
('2 Kings', 24, 'adults', 8, 'How does the removal of the temple vessels and cutting of Solomon''s golden vessels in chapter 24 foreshadow the complete destruction of chapter 25?', 'It represents the first phase of the temple''s despoliation — the stripping of its wealth — before the second and final phase of its physical destruction, showing a progressive intensification of divine judgment', 'It fulfilled a specific prophecy of Isaiah that the vessels would be taken before the building was burned', 'It was an act of mercy allowing the sacred objects to survive even if the building was destroyed', 'It had no symbolic significance and was purely motivated by Babylon''s greed', 'a', 'Nebuchadnezzar cut in pieces all the vessels of gold (2 Kings 24:13) in this first deportation; chapter 25 records the temple itself being burned and the remaining bronze pillars carried to Babylon (2 Kings 25:13-17), completing the progressive dismantling of Solomon''s temple.');

-- ═══ 2 Kings Chapter 25 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Kings', 25, 'kids', 1, 'What did the Babylonians do to the temple in Jerusalem?', 'They burned the house of the LORD with fire', 'They carried it stone by stone to Babylon', 'They turned it into a palace for the governor', 'They filled it with Babylonian idols', 'a', 'He burnt the house of the LORD, and the king''s house, and all the houses of Jerusalem, and every great man''s house burnt he with fire (2 Kings 25:9).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'kids', 2, 'What happened to King Zedekiah when the Babylonians caught him?', 'They killed his sons before his eyes, then put out his eyes and bound him in chains', 'He was taken to Babylon and made a servant of the king', 'He was killed immediately at the walls of Jerusalem', 'He was allowed to live in peace in Jerusalem', 'a', 'They slew the sons of Zedekiah before his eyes, and put out the eyes of Zedekiah, and bound him with fetters of brass, and carried him to Babylon (2 Kings 25:7).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'kids', 3, 'Who was the kind foreign king who freed Jehoiachin from prison at the end of the book?', 'Evil-merodach king of Babylon', 'Cyrus king of Persia', 'Darius the Mede', 'Artaxerxes king of Persia', 'a', 'Evil-merodach king of Babylon in the year that he began to reign did lift up the head of Jehoiachin king of Judah out of prison (2 Kings 25:27).'),
-- Teens
('2 Kings', 25, 'teens', 1, 'In what year of Zedekiah''s reign did Nebuchadnezzar come with all his army and besiege Jerusalem?', 'The ninth year, tenth month, tenth day', 'The seventh year, fifth month, first day', 'The eleventh year, fourth month, ninth day', 'The fifth year, third month, seventeenth day', 'a', 'In the ninth year of his reign, in the tenth month, in the tenth day of the month, that Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came, he, and all his host, against Jerusalem (2 Kings 25:1).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'teens', 2, 'Through which gate did Zedekiah flee Jerusalem, and where was he overtaken?', 'The gate between two walls; the plains of Jericho', 'The fish gate; the valley of the Jordan', 'The sheep gate; the wilderness of Judah', 'The water gate; the Dead Sea shore', 'a', 'The king went the way toward the plain...And the army of the Chaldees pursued after the king, and overtook him in the plains of Jericho (2 Kings 25:4-5).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'teens', 3, 'Who was Nebuzar-adan and what was his role?', 'The captain of the guard; he was the Babylonian officer who burned Jerusalem and oversaw the deportation', 'The chief priest of Babylon who supervised the destruction of the temple', 'A Babylonian general who commanded the army besieging Jerusalem', 'The governor appointed over the remaining people of Judah', 'a', 'Nebuzar-adan, captain of the guard, a servant of the king of Babylon, came unto Jerusalem: And he burnt the house of the LORD (2 Kings 25:8-9).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'teens', 4, 'Who was appointed governor over the people who remained in Judah?', 'Gedaliah the son of Ahikam', 'Nebuzar-adan the captain of the guard', 'An unnamed Babylonian official', 'Johanan the son of Careah', 'a', 'Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon made Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, the son of Shaphan, ruler over the people (2 Kings 25:22).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'teens', 5, 'What was the final act of hope at the end of 2 Kings?', 'Evil-merodach lifted up Jehoiachin''s head, released him from prison, spoke kindly to him, and gave him a seat above all the kings with him in Babylon', 'A remnant returned from Babylon to Jerusalem to rebuild the altar', 'A prophet declared that Israel would be restored within seventy years', 'Gedaliah rebuilt the walls of Jerusalem with the remaining people', 'a', 'Evil-merodach king of Babylon...did lift up the head of Jehoiachin king of Judah out of prison...And changed his prison garments: and he did eat bread continually before him all the days of his life (2 Kings 25:27-29).'),
-- Adults
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 1, 'How long was Jerusalem besieged and what finally broke the city''s resistance?', 'The siege lasted until the eleventh year of Zedekiah; the famine prevailed in the city and there was no bread for the people', 'The siege lasted two years until Babylon destroyed the aqueducts', 'The city fell in six months when its garrison mutinied', 'Jerusalem held out for three years until Egypt failed to send relief', 'a', 'The city was besieged unto the eleventh year of king Zedekiah. And on the ninth day of the fourth month the famine prevailed in the city, and there was no bread for the people of the land (2 Kings 25:2-3).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 2, 'What was the fate of Seraiah the chief priest and Zephaniah the second priest?', 'Nebuzar-adan took them to Nebuchadnezzar at Riblah, and Nebuchadnezzar put them to death', 'They were taken captive to Babylon along with the nobles', 'They escaped with Zedekiah toward the Jordan', 'They were placed under house arrest in the ruined temple', 'a', 'Nebuzar-adan the captain of the guard took Seraiah the chief priest, and Zephaniah the second priest...And he carried them to the king of Babylon to Riblah: and the king of Babylon smote them, and slew them at Riblah (2 Kings 25:18, 20-21).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 3, 'What happened to the bronze pillars, the sea, and the bases Solomon had made for the temple?', 'The Chaldees brake them in pieces, and carried the brass of them to Babylon', 'They were buried under the temple floor by the priests before the Babylonians arrived', 'They were taken whole to Babylon and placed in Nebuchadnezzar''s palace', 'They were melted down in Jerusalem and the metal used to pay the army', 'a', 'The pillars of brass that were in the house of the LORD, and the bases, and the brasen sea that was in the house of the LORD, did the Chaldees break in pieces, and carried the brass of them to Babylon (2 Kings 25:13).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 4, 'Who murdered Gedaliah the governor and what was the consequence for the remaining people of Judah?', 'Ishmael the son of Nethaniah of the royal seed smote him; and all the people, both small and great, and the captains of the forces arose and came to Egypt for fear of the Chaldees', 'Unnamed bandits killed Gedaliah and the people dispersed to surrounding nations', 'The captain Johanan killed Gedaliah and established his own rule over Judah', 'The Ammonites killed Gedaliah and Nebuchadnezzar appointed a new governor', 'a', 'Ishmael the son of Nethaniah...came, and ten men with him, and smote Gedaliah...And all the people, both small and great, and the captains of the forces, arose, and came to Egypt: for they were afraid of the Chaldees (2 Kings 25:25-26).'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 5, 'How does the detail of the pillar measurements in verses 17-22 function literarily in the conclusion of Kings?', 'It echoes the original construction account in 1 Kings 7, forming a literary inclusio that marks the complete reversal of the Solomonic era — what Solomon built, Babylon destroyed', 'It serves as a historical inventory for the exilic community to catalogue their losses', 'It proves that the author was an eyewitness to the temple''s destruction', 'It fulfils a specific law requiring all temple measurements to be recorded', 'a', 'The detailed pillar measurements (2 Kings 25:17) recall 1 Kings 7:15-16 where Solomon first erected them, forming a deliberate literary bracket showing the full dissolution of Solomon''s kingdom and temple — the theological nadir of the entire narrative of Kings.'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 6, 'What is the significance of Nebuchadnezzar being at Riblah as the place where judgment on Judah''s leaders was executed?', 'Riblah was also where Pharaoh-nechoh had bound Jehoahaz after Josiah''s death — making it the place where both Egyptian and Babylonian overlords executed their authority over Judah, symbolising complete subjugation', 'Riblah was chosen because it was the geographic centre between Judah and Babylon', 'Riblah was the sacred city of the Aramean gods and executions there were ritual acts', 'Riblah had no particular significance and was simply a convenient military headquarters', 'a', 'Nebuchadnezzar slew Judah''s leaders at Riblah (2 Kings 25:20-21), the same place Pharaoh-nechoh had deposed Jehoahaz (2 Kings 23:33), showing that Judah had become utterly subject first to Egypt and then to Babylon — both empires exercising life-and-death power at the same northern Syrian location.'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 7, 'What does the release of Jehoiachin in verses 27-30 contribute to the theological conclusion of Kings?', 'It ends the book on a note of restrained hope — the Davidic line is not extinct but surviving, even if in exile, leaving open the possibility of future fulfilment of the covenant promises to David', 'It proves that Babylon had repented of its destruction of Jerusalem', 'It fulfils Jeremiah''s prophecy that Jehoiachin would return to Jerusalem within his lifetime', 'It shows that the exile was ending and the return under Zerubbabel was imminent', 'a', 'Evil-merodach lifted up the head of Jehoiachin and set his throne above the kings with him in Babylon (2 Kings 25:28), ending the book not in total despair but with the Davidic heir surviving — a fragile but real sign that the covenant with David (2 Samuel 7) had not been finally revoked.'),
('2 Kings', 25, 'adults', 8, 'How does the fall of Jerusalem in 586 BC function as the theological climax not only of 2 Kings but of the entire Deuteronomistic History from Deuteronomy through Kings?', 'It demonstrates that the covenant curses of Deuteronomy 28-29 were fully enacted — the nation received every threatened judgment for persistent unfaithfulness, validating both God''s justice and His word through Moses and the prophets', 'It proves that God had permanently abandoned Israel with no future restoration', 'It shows that the Mosaic covenant was inferior to the later Davidic covenant which ultimately prevailed', 'It ends the historical narrative without any theological conclusion, leaving the reader to draw their own interpretation', 'a', 'The fall of Jerusalem (2 Kings 25) fulfils Deuteronomy 28:36, 64 — the king taken captive, the people scattered among the nations — vindicating every covenant warning from Moses through the classical prophets, while the survival of the Davidic heir (2 Kings 25:27-30) sustains hope for the new covenant and Messianic fulfilment foreshadowed throughout the entire History.');
